    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-16T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-16T13:00:00-05:00" n="167"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d167">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">868.00/12–1544: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Greece</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-16T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >December 16, 1944—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>124. Reurtel 150, December 15. Suggested solution appears to be most promising
                    proposal yet advanced and closely parallels Department’s ideas already
                    communicated to the British. Department is appreciatively aware of the
                    difficulty of your position during this critical period when communications have
                    been interrupted and when confused propaganda in Greece has misinterpreted
                    certain United States statements and fundamental policy. Your correct
                    reaffirmation of Department’s views has been most helpful.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
